Locality: Jordan River Parkway--4500 S to 5400 S (incl. Arrowhead Park)
Observation Details: All in one group moving together. Unusual at this elevation. Last falls conifer cone crop in the Wasatch was a near complete failure, and many STJA left the mountains and came to lower elevations looking for an alternate food,which is not to unusual. However, in most years these altitudal invasions occur mostly to our foothills and lower mountains where they use Gambel's Oak acorns as an alternate food, but last falls acorn crop was also very meager, and so STJA and WOSJ have turned up in even lower altitudes, invading neighborhoods and even the Jordan River bottoms looking for food. This past winter I have had them at multiple locations on the Jordan River, which is unprecedented in my 25 years of birding the Wasatch front.

Observation Details: Yard list first, number 97! This has been an unprecedented fall for high-altitude birds moving down into the valley. I saw one of this species on campus earlier the same morning and was just thinking that this was likely to be the next new species to appear on the yard list. Aged as hatch-year by pink gape. I think the bold white spot above the eye and small white spot below the eye indicate subspecies C. s. macrolopha, expected in most or all of Utah, but the pale blue (rather than pale white) stripes on the forehead indicate C. s. annectens, expected in Idaho, making this a likely intergrade between the two subspecies. Both of these subspecies are in the interior "C. s. diademata group." Photographed:

Observation Details: * UPDATE 1.25.19: Bird continuing at this location, and continues to be affiliated with a consistent small winter flock/group of 3 blue jays, who cooperatively "scout" for food, threats, etc.  The Steller's does little vocalizing (from what I've heard; other visiting birders have heard it); vocalizing is usually from one of the blue jays...typically the one "keeping watch" as the others feed.  Interestingly the Steller's seems dominant (or at least appears deferred to) in this small group, almost always feeding first before the others.  Original 10.8.18 sighting/entry: Appears to be an adult (Interior) male? Very similar situation to what is described in Sam Manning’s 1.3.14 submission/checklist S16234143 (Old Stage Hill Road and Ken Strey’s feeders are within ½ mile of this location).  This bird was feeding with a small flock of blue jays.  Unlike the noisier and far more assertive blue jays, this Steller’s never made a sound and was more stealthy/secretive in approaching the feeder from the nearby ravine.  The Steller’s would fly up from the ravine to the Ponderosa closest to the feeder, hop a few branches, then down to the ground to forage for the peanuts; unlike the blue jays it wouldn’t take peanuts from the wreath feeder.  Gorgeous bird on a cold and rainy day!

* UPDATE 1.25.19: Bird continuing at this location, and continues to be affiliated with a consistent small winter flock/group of 3 blue jays, who cooperatively "scout" for food, threats, etc.  The Steller's does little vocalizing (from what I've heard; other visiting birders have heard it); vocalizing is usually from one of the blue jays...typically the one "keeping watch" as the others feed.  Interestingly the Steller's seems dominant (or at least appears deferred to) in this small group, almost always feeding first before the others.  Original 10.8.18 sighting/entry: Appears to be an adult (Interior) male? Very similar situation to what is described in Sam Manning’s 1.3.14 submission/checklist S16234143 (Old Stage Hill Road and Ken Strey’s feeders are within ½ mile of this location).  This bird was feeding with a small flock of blue jays.  Unlike the noisier and far more assertive blue jays, this Steller’s never made a sound and was more stealthy/secretive in approaching the feeder from the nearby ravine.  The Steller’s would fly up from the ravine to the Ponderosa closest to the feeder, hop a few branches, then down to the ground to forage for the peanuts; unlike the blue jays it wouldn’t take peanuts from the wreath feeder.  Gorgeous bird on a cold and rainy day!

Media notes: The Steller's Jays on my property are less aggressive than the Western Scrub Jays.There have been up to four Stellers on the feeder and one on top of the feeder pole at one time.
Observation Details: These birds are not rare on my property this time of year. My highest count this year at one time is 10 - in January.  Counted 8 just today which is March 1st. Based on their behavior (and one young Jay who has a hoarse voice) I believe some of these are the same we had last year at this time.  Last year they arrived in November and stayed through April.  I have many pictures to document this if you're interested (and some good ones, am not lucky with good ones on the count days!)This year they came  in early September ( I have the exact date) -We did have some very cold mornings - down to 22..  They come down from a higher elevation above 3,500 feet.  Even though the Audubon society doesn't consider the Steller's Jay migratory  - they are.  They are typically found above 3500 feet here we are at about 1750 feet..  Last year is the first year I've seen a large number on my  property (used to be only one or 2 each year).  We live on acreage with many tall oaks and pines and a finger of a lake which is owned by Nevada Irrigation District approx 300 yards from here.  I live in an area designated as a Bird Sanctuary. I do not live in a subdivision.  There are many dense blackberry bushes, and a variety of pines, oaks and cedars in this area.  We are a haven for Acorn Woodpeckers, Hawks, Jays, Raven's, Crows Etc.   I would be happy to provide many pictures from this time of year for birds you consider rare.

This was my last day of a 12-day trip to Washington.  Steller's were high on my wish-list to see (Lifer) and hoped for solid images.  Yard birds at my friends' home in Seattle, but they didn't show when I was there. My friend sent nice pics from the kitchen window and again from the garden as time went by and I still hadn't seen them.  My trip included Orcas Island, and while other folks got to see them up close, not me.  The start of this day, I chased a raptor who flew by as we parked.  Returning to the car a couple minutes later, my friend had cell phone pics of a Steller's that watched her change clothes in the parking lot while I had stepped away!  Never thought Steller's would be the trip species most difficult to get!  As we hiked to the car at the end of our last day, they were back at the parking lot!   A closer look at the last image, ....2800.jpg and you see the insect that the Jay was watching!

Media notes: Steller’s Jay choosing a peanut
Observation Details: Something is going on with Woodward and Bernstein. Bernstein has been coming alone, with Woodward leaving for long periods of time; they might have been there together for 10 minutes of the hour and forty five I was there with at least one of them. Bernstein won’t come as close to me as Woodward, so I am relatively certain Woodward, the female, it is the one away most of the time. Bernstein had arguments with other species twice today. Mae got in his face when he arrived, while Bernstein stood a branch above squawking and pecking the branch he was on with his beak. Eventually Mae just went and got a peanut and flew away. The second time he flew into the stand of spruce trees typically inhabited by a single towhee, and was chased away by two. They were far more aggressive with him than Mae was though. I’ve been trying to trace where Woodward and Bernstein come from first thing in the morning to find where they roost at night but they have been arriving silently. It’s the first time I’ve put the sound the Steller’s makes in the 8 second clip in Merlin. It comes back as a Cooler’s hawk but I’m not convinced it’s intended as an impersonation. They have impersonated a red-tailed call to disperse squirrels.

White mark over eye and thin white arc under eye; crest with frontal lines whitish but perhaps bluish tinged on highest portion (most distal); grayish-white broken streaks on throat. This bird is probably closest to C. s. macrolopha of the interior montane group of subspecies from northern Mexico north. Perhaps uncommon at this lower elevation and location but probably not unexpected in winter. In addition to white marks around the eyes, the calls were quite distinctive from coastal subspecies with which I am most familiar.

Media notes: Steller's Jay at Ketchikan - at best an intergrade stelleri x   annectens; white eyebrows more prominent on the right side of the bird's head than the left side.
Observation Details: One Steller's Jay at Herring Cove with white eyebrows, potential intergrade stelleri x annectens.  The white feathering was stronger on the right side of the bird's head, much less so on the left side.  Certainly not a pure annectens (and a weak example of an intergrade) but thought it was worth reporting as a potential intergrade.  Started looking at jays a lot closer after Kaylauna Warren photographed potential interior birds at Wrangell last fall.  Intergrades are well known from the Skeena River valley, British Columbia, including at coast just south of Ketchikan at Prince Rupert (Swarth 1936, Proc. Cal. Acad. Sci. p. 69; Weibe 1995, British Columbia Birds 5:3-11; Stevenson 1934; Condor 36:72-78.).  Also, jays were in very low numbers in the Ketchikan area all winter, but started to increase in numbers since late March.

Observation Details: * UPDATE 1.25.19: Bird continuing at this location, and continues to be affiliated with a consistent small winter flock/group of 3 blue jays, who cooperatively "scout" for food, threats, etc.  The Steller's does little vocalizing (from what I've heard; other visiting birders have heard it); vocalizing is usually from one of the blue jays...typically the one "keeping watch" as the others feed.  Interestingly the Steller's seems dominant (or at least appears deferred to) in this small group, almost always feeding first before the others.  Original 10.8.18 sighting/entry: Appears to be an adult (Interior) male? Very similar situation to what is described in Sam Manning’s 1.3.14 submission/checklist S16234143 (Old Stage Hill Road and Ken Strey’s feeders are within ½ mile of this location).  This bird was feeding with a small flock of blue jays.  Unlike the noisier and far more assertive blue jays, this Steller’s never made a sound and was more stealthy/secretive in approaching the feeder from the nearby ravine.  The Steller’s would fly up from the ravine to the Ponderosa closest to the feeder, hop a few branches, then down to the ground to forage for the peanuts; unlike the blue jays it wouldn’t take peanuts from the wreath feeder.  Gorgeous bird on a cold and rainy day!

RARE: Steller's Jay ... at 4ave/1 St SW ... Photos attached.   FIELD NOTES:  SIZE: about 10-12" head to tail, roughly Blue Jay, Stellar Jay size.  SHAPE: Crested black head  COLOUR PATTERN: charcoal head/dark blue body, dark eyes, very small white tuft beside eye, and slight white tuft between eyes.   BEHAVIOUR: It was making a lot of noise in a spruce tree, flew across the street into a 15' leafless deciduous tree, where it made a lot more noise ... before flying into the back yard, where there is a feeder. Was searching the grass, hopping along . I followed this bird for the next 20 minutes, as it went back and forth across the street between these two locations, taking photos - no luck on an audio. It appeared quite busy in the spruce tree.   VOCALIZATION: I heard it's rapid fire call, compared it to Sibley sounds: verified it as a Stellar's Jay.  HABITAT: Older area of town with many mature spruce, mtn ash, various bushes and poplar trees.  OTHER SIGHTINGS: - I saw and reported a Steller's Jay to eBird in this same location Oct 14 2024 - I saw and reported a Steller's Jay to eBird in this same location Dec 26 2023

Media notes: Steller's Jay at Ketchikan - at best an intergrade stelleri x   annectens; white eyebrows more prominent on the right side of the bird's head than the left side.
Observation Details: One Steller's Jay at Herring Cove with white eyebrows, potential intergrade stelleri x annectens.  The white feathering was stronger on the right side of the bird's head, much less so on the left side.  Certainly not a pure annectens (and a weak example of an intergrade) but thought it was worth reporting as a potential intergrade.  Started looking at jays a lot closer after Kaylauna Warren photographed potential interior birds at Wrangell last fall.  Intergrades are well known from the Skeena River valley, British Columbia, including at coast just south of Ketchikan at Prince Rupert (Swarth 1936, Proc. Cal. Acad. Sci. p. 69; Weibe 1995, British Columbia Birds 5:3-11; Stevenson 1934; Condor 36:72-78.).  Also, jays were in very low numbers in the Ketchikan area all winter, but started to increase in numbers since late March.

Observation Details: This was my last day of a 12-day trip to Washington.  Steller's were high on my wish-list to see (Lifer) and hoped for solid images.  Yard birds at my friends' home in Seattle, but they didn't show when I was there. My friend sent nice pics from the kitchen window and again from the garden as time went by and I still hadn't seen them.  My trip included Orcas Island, and while other folks got to see them up close, not me.  The start of this day, I chased a raptor who flew by as we parked.  Returning to the car a couple minutes later, my friend had cell phone pics of a Steller's that watched her change clothes in the parking lot while I had stepped away!  Never thought Steller's would be the trip species most difficult to get!  As we hiked to the car at the end of our last day, they were back at the parking lot!   A closer look at the last image, ....2800.jpg and you see the insect that the Jay was watching!

Returning to the car a couple minutes later, my friend had cell phone pics of a Steller's that watched her change clothes in the parking lot while I had stepped away!  Never thought Steller's would be the trip species most difficult to get!  As we hiked to the car at the end of our last day, they were back at the parking lot!   A closer look at the last image, ....2800.jpg and you see the insect that the Jay was watching!
